Then, the four points are: z1: (a, b) z2: (a, -b) 1/z1: (a/10, -b/10 ) 1/z2: (a/10, b/10 ) So, the four points are: A: (a, b) B: (a, -b) C: (a/10, b/10 ) D: (a/10, -b/10 ) To compute the area of quadrilateral ABCD, we can use the shoelace formula. Let's list the coordinates in order. Let's assume the order is A, B, D, C. So: A: (a, b) B: (a, -b) D: (a/10, -b/10 ) C: (a/10, b/10 ) Shoelace formula: Area = 1/2 | (x_A y_B + x_B y_D + x_D y_C + x_C y_A ) - (y_A x_B + y_B x_D + y_D x_C + y_C x_A ) | Compute each term: First part: x_A y_B = a*(-b) = -ab x_B y_D = a*(-b/10 ) = -ab/10 x_D y_C = (a/10)*(b/10 ) = ab/100 x_C y_A = (a/10)*b = ab/10 Second part: y_A x_B = b*a = ab y_B x_D = (-b)*(a/10 ) = -ab/
